Since Life Expectancy is negatively skewed, I will calculate the median and mode for the target variable to decide the most appropriate value for filling the missing data.

In[14]:
# Calculate the median for Life expectancy
median_life_expectancy = df['Life expectancy '].median()

# Calculate the mode for Life expectancy
mode_life_expectancy = df['Life expectancy '].mode()[0]  # mode() returns a series, take the first mode value

print(f"Median Life expectancy: {median_life_expectancy}")
print(f"Mode Life expectancy: {mode_life_expectancy}")

Median Life expectancy: 72.1
Mode Life expectancy: 73.0

The median and mode values for Life Expectancy are almost identical. After analyzing the heatmap and histogram with skewness, filling the missing values for Life Expectancy with the median is the better choice.

For the other columns, the approach is as follows:

If the skewness value is between -0.5 and 0.5, fill missing values with the mean. Otherwise, fill missing values with the median

In[15]:

In[16]:
# Iterate over all columns to check skewness and fill missing values
for column in df.columns:
    # Check if the column has missing values
    if df[column].isnull().sum() > 0:
        # Check skewness of the column
        skewness = df[column].skew()

        # If the skewness is negative (Left-skewed) or positive (Right-skewed), fill with median
        if skewness < -0.5 or skewness > 0.5:
            df[column].fillna(df[column].median(), inplace=True)
        # If the skewness is near zero (Normal), fill with mean
        else:
            df[column].fillna(df[column].mean(), inplace=True)

# Check if any missing values remain
df.isnull().sum()

# prompt: Check Multicollinearity in X

from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor

# Select only numerical features for VIF calculation
numerical_X = X.select_dtypes(include=[np.number])

# Calculate VIF for each independent variable
vif = pd.DataFrame()
vif["VIF Factor"] = [variance_inflation_factor(numerical_X.values, i) for i in range(numerical_X.shape[1])]
vif["features"] = numerical_X.columns

# Display the VIF values
print(vif)

# Identify variables with high VIF (e.g., > 5 or 10)
high_vif_variables = vif[vif["VIF Factor"] > 5]["features"].tolist()
print("\nVariables with high VIF:", high_vif_variables)

VIF Analysis: Taking all the required actions to handle multicollinearity because it directly impacts the model's performance and interpretability. Since the target variable is Life Expectancy, ensuring that the independent variables are not highly correlated is crucial for obtaining meaningful results.

To this end:

Removing redundant variables, such as one of the dummy variables

  1. (Status_Developed or Status_Developing) and choosing between highly correlated variables like infant deaths and under-five deaths.
  2. For skewed variables like GDP, I am applying transformations to reduce their influence.
  3. I am combining or removing overlapping metrics like thinness 1-19 years and thinness 5-9 years to simplify the model.
  4. Finally, I am recalculating VIF to confirm that multicollinearity is resolved, ensuring the model focuses on variables that truly contribute to predicting Life Expectancy."

# OLS Regression
ols_model = sm.OLS(y_continuous, X).fit()

# Predict with OLS model
y_pred_ols = ols_model.predict(X)

# Calculate RMSE and R-squared
rmse_ols = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_continuous, y_pred_ols))
r2_ols = r2_score(y_continuous, y_pred_ols)

Precision (0.8661): This measures the proportion of positive predictions (i.e., the predicted positive class) that were actually correct. In this case, 86.61% of the instances predicted as positive are truly positive. Precision is important when the cost of false positives is high (e.g., when predicting diseases or fraud).

Recall (0.9045): This measures the proportion of actual positive instances that were correctly identified by the model. In this case, 90.45% of the true positive instances were correctly classified as positive. Recall is important when the cost of false negatives is high (e.g., missing a disease diagnosis).

Analysis

The provided visualizations show the performance of the model from different perspectives. From the confusion matrix, the overall good accuracy of the model, with a very high number of correct predictions in both classes, is evident. The ROC-AUC further cements this very good performance and presents very good discriminatory power with an AUC of 0.95, hence this model is able to differentiate well between positive and negative instances across a wide range of classification thresholds. The distribution of predicted probabilities indicates that this model is well-calibrated; it assigns higher probabilities to the instances which actually belong to the positive class and lower probabilities to those belonging to the negative class. That would mean the model is pretty aware of the underlying patterns and is likely to make reliable predictions. Overall, the model presents robust performance and can be viewed as a reliable tool in classification tasks.
